The `unselectable='on'` attribute is often used to prevent text selection on an element. This can be useful for elements like icons or other non-text elements where you do not want the user to accidentally select the content.

If you would like to change or remove this attribute from the container with the icon of the arrow in your react component using the rc-select library, you can do so using React's `ref` system. Here's an example of how you can access the DOM node of the container and remove the `unselectable` attribute:

```jsx
import React, { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
import Select from 'rc-select';

const MySelect = () => {
  const containerRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (containerRef.current) {
      containerRef.current.removeAttribute('unselectable');
    }
  }, []);

  return (
    <div ref={containerRef}>
      <Select />
    </div>
  );
}

export default MySelect;
```

In this example, we're creating a `ref` called `containerRef` and attaching it to the `<div>` element that wraps the `Select` component. We then use `useEffect` to wait for the element to be rendered, and then call `removeAttribute('unselectable')` on the DOM node of the container to remove the `unselectable` attribute.

This should allow you to change or remove the `unselectable` attribute from the container with the arrow icon in your react component using the rc-select library.

