In this example, we're using the `useLayoutEffect` hook, which is called synchronously after all DOM mutations. This ensures that the DOM node is available when trying to remove the `unselectable` attribute. The rest of the implementation is similar to the `useEffect` example provided earlier.

Using `useLayoutEffect` may be more appropriate if you want the removal of the `unselectable` attribute to happen synchronously after the component is rendered and before the browser paints the screen.

Yes, you can remove the `unselectable` attribute using styled components in React. Styled components allow you to create styled versions of existing HTML elements and apply custom styles to them.

Here's an example of how you can remove the `unselectable` attribute using styled components:

```jsx
import styled from 'styled-components';
import Select from 'rc-select';

const Container = styled.div`
  &[unselectable] {
    -moz-user-select: none;
    -webkit-user-select: none;
    -ms-user-select: none;
