```

In this example, we are creating a styled component called `Container` using styled components. We define the styles for the `unselectable` attribute using the `&[unselectable]` selector in the styled component. Inside the styles, we set the `user-select` property to `none` to prevent text selection.

By using styled components in this way, you can customize the styles of the container element while also potentially addressing the issue of the `unselectable` attribute. This approach leverages the power and flexibility of styled components in React to style the component and manage attributes like `unselectable`.

To write a function in your React app that will console.log an element when you click on it, you can attach an `onClick` event handler to the element and call a function that logs the element. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

const handleClick = (event) => {
  console.log(event.target);
}

const MyComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1 onClick={handleClick}>Click me to log this element</h1>
      <p onClick={handleClick}>Click me to log this element</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, we have defined a function called `handleClick` that takes an `event` parameter. This function logs the `event.target`, which represents the element that triggered the event (in this case, the element that was clicked).

We then attach the `onClick` event handler to the `<h1>` and `<p>` elements in the `MyComponent`. When you click on these elements, the `handleClick` function will be called, and the console will log the element that was clicked.

You can modify this function to log other properties or information about the element, depending on your requirements.

To attach a `handleClick` event to the arrow in the `rc-select` component and close the menu of options when clicking on the arrow, you can use a combination of `ref` and event handling in React.

Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```jsx
import React, { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
import Select from 'rc-select';


const MySelect = () => {
  const selectRef = useRef(null);

  const handleClick = (event) => {
    if (selectRef.current && !selectRef.current.contains(event.target)) {
      selectRef.current.onDropdownVisibleChange(false);
    }
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    document.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
    return () => {
      document.removeEventListener('click', handleClick);
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <Select ref={selectRef} />
  );
}

export default MySelect;
```

In this example, we are using a `ref` called `selectRef` to get a reference to the `Select` component rendered by the `rc-select` library. We then define a `handleClick` function that will close the dropdown menu if the click event target is not inside the `Select` component.

We use `useEffect` to add an event listener for clicks on the document and call the `handleClick` function. This allows us to close the dropdown menu when clicking outside of the `Select` component, including on the arrow.

By following this approach, you can create a solution to close the dropdown menu of the `rc-select` component when clicking on the arrow inside the input field.

